OpenGL
•OpenGL is an API for graphics rendering. It is a hardware independent
specification not a programing language
•GPUs manufacturers are responsible for writing implementations (drivers)
for their OpenGL rendering system.
•Software implementation such as Mesa 3D are available
•The OpenGL drivers translate OpenGL commands to GPU commands
•Today we will be calling the OpenGL libraries from Python
Brief History
•OpenGL v1.0 released in 1992 used fixed function pipeline
•OpenGL v2.0 introduced the OpenGL Shading Language (also called GLSL)
•OpenGL v3.0 deprecated several features of the previous versions
•Several versions released, latest is v4.6
•Active development of OpenGL was dropped in favor of the Vulkan API,
released in 2016
•OpenGL is still very useful and supported by new GPUs
Windows Manager
•OpenGL is Window and OS independent, it does not provided a window
management functionality so another library such as GLUT (The OpenGL
Utility Toolkit), QT will be required to manage the windows
•We will be using PyQt as our windows manager.
•After creating a window, a GL context should be initialized which stores all
of the state associated with this instance of OpenGL
•Then you must make the GL context current every time you draw. In QT,
this is managed by the QOpenGLWidget Class
Create a Window
class GLWidget(QtOpenGLWidgets.QOpenGLWidget):

print(f"The size of the GL Widget is ({width},{height})")

Shaders
•Shader is a user-defined program designed to run on some stage of a
graphics processor.
•Shaders are written in the OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL)
•GLSL is a C like language with which the transformation and fragment
shading stages of the pipeline can be programmed.
•A program combines multiple shader stages into a single linked whole.
Basic shader
#version 330
const vec2 vertices[4] = vec2[4](vec2(-1.0, -1.0), vec2(1.0, -1.0), vec2(-
1.0,1.0), vec2(1.0,1.0));
void main()
{
gl_Position = vec4(vertices[gl_VertexID], 0.0,1.0);
}
#version 330
out vec4 colour;
void main(){
colour = vec4(1,0,0,1);
}

Uniform
•A uniform is a global shader variable declared with "uniform" storage
qualifier.
•These act as parameters that the user of a shader program can pass to that
program (see 2_Uniform.py)
colourLoc = GL.glGetUniformLocation(self.program_id, "colour")
GL.glUniform3fv(colourLoc, 1, np.random.rand(3))
#version 330
uniform vec3 colour;
out vec4 fragColour;
void main(){
fragColour = vec4(colour, 1.0);
}

Primitives

•Points
•Lines
•Triangles
•Quads (Deprecated)
So far we have used GL.glDrawArrays to
draw Triangle Strip
Vertex Buffer
•So far the vertex have been set in the vertex shader but it is more common
and practical to pass the vertex data to the shader using vertex buffer
objects (VBOs). To use them we
1. Create and initialize a buffer object glGenBuffers
2. Bind the buffer to GL_ARRAY_BUFFER and load data into it (glBindBuffer &
glBufferData)
3. Add a vertex attribute variable to the vertex shader. Get the location with
glGetAttribLocation
4. When drawing, enable the location glEnableVertexAttribArray
5. Rebind the buffer and provide information about how the data should be read
glVertexAttribPointer
6. Draw the primitive
OpenGL as a State Machine
•While drawing, OpenGL behaves like a state machine, where the current
state influences the output
•For example, after binding a buffer it will stay bound until it is unbound or a
different buffer is bound.
•This state remains active until it is changed by another graphics command
•This can be the source of bugs when state is not reset or disable correctly
GL.glBindBuffer(GL.GL_ARRAY_BUFFER, self.vertex_buffer)
…
GL.glBindBuffer(GL.GL_ARRAY_BUFFER, GL.GL_FALSE)

3D
•To draw 3d objects, we simply update the vertices with the z values
•OpenGL stores all its depth information in a z-buffer, also known as a depth
buffer. The z value are used to perform depth testing which ensure
fragments behind are not drawn but discarded
•Depth testing should be enabled with glEnable(GL_DEPTH_TEST) then
the buffer cleared before drawing
GL.glClear(GL.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT | GL.GL_DEPTH_BUFFER_BIT)
Element Buffer
•As the number of face increases, a vertices might be belong to multiple faces
and duplicating the vertices will increase the memory usage. It is possible to
use a single vertex in multiple face with element buffer. To do this
1. Create and initialize a buffer object glGenBuffers
2. Bind the buffer to GL_ELEMENT_ARRAY_BUFFER and load data into it
(glBindBuffer & glBufferData)
3. When drawing, rebind the buffer and draw the primitive with glDrawElements

Texture
•Texture or uv coordinates are used to tell location in the image should be
assigned to a vertex. The texture colour for a fragment is determined by
interpolating the uv coordinates belonging to the vertex of the face
•Create texture object glGenTextures and Load Image
•Bind texture object and copy image to GPU
(GL.glBindTexture & GL.glTexImage2D)
•Assign uv coordinates to vertices
•Update fragment shader to use texture (Sampler2D)
•Activate texture unit, bind texture and draw as usual.

Text
•OpenGL doesn't support font rendering. There are a few ways to render text
1. Texture based rendering: create texture of individual characters or sentence then
render that on a plane in the scene.
2. Outline Fonts: describe the character outlines with a combination of control
points and curves, then convert the characters into polygons for rendering
•With Qt, the QPainter can be used to draw on the OpenGL frame buffer
which is useful for simply cases.
